  "text": "## Configuration Hot-Reload Implementation Patterns\n\n### Kubernetes Implementation\n\n**File Watcher Setup:**\nKubernetes uses `github.com/fsnotify/fsnotify` for watching file changes. The pattern is demonstrated in three key files:\n\n1. `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/dynamiccertificates/dynamic_cafile_content.go` - Implements `watchCAFile()` method that creates an fsnotify.Watcher, adds the CA file to watch, and handles fsnotify.Events in a select loop. Events trigger `handleWatchEvent()` which queues work items for processing.\n\n2. `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/dynamiccertificates/dynamic_serving_content.go` - Similar pattern with `watchCertKeyFile()` watching both cert and key files. Uses `workqueue.TypedRateLimitingInterface` for queueing reload work items.\n\n**Config Diff Detection:**\nKubernetes implements byte-level comparison for change detection:\n\n1. `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/dynamiccertificates/dynamic_cafile_content.go` - The `hasCAChanged()` method uses `bytes.Equal()` to compare the new CA bundle with the currently stored value in `atomic.Value`. Only proceeds with reload if content differs.\n\n2. `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/options/encryptionconfig/config.go` - The `GetEncryptionConfigHash()` function computes SHA256 hash of encryption config file. The hash serves as a cheap check to determine if the file has changed.\n\n3. `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/options/encryptionconfig/controller/controller.go` - The `processEncryptionConfig()` method performs a two-stage diff check: first comparing content hash before loading (fast), then comparing the loaded configuration's hash after loading to avoid TOCTOU issues.\n\n**Atomic Config Swap:**\nKubernetes uses Go's `sync/atomic.Value` for atomic config updates:\n\n1. `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/dynamiccertificates/dynamic_cafile_content.go` - Stores parsed CA bundle in `atomic.Value` with `caBundle.Store(caBundleAndVerifier)`. Clients read via `CurrentCABundleContent()` which calls `caBundle.Load()`.\n\n2. `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/dynamiccertificates/tlsconfig.go` - The `syncCerts()` method:\n   - Calls `newTLSContent()` to build new TLS config\n   - Uses `newContent.Equal(c.currentlyServedContent)` to detect changes\n   - Parses new certs into a cloned base TLS config\n   - Atomically swaps config via `c.currentServingTLSConfig.Store(newTLSConfigCopy)` (line 227)\n   - Uses `GetConfigForClient()` callback to serve latest config without restarting TLS listeners\n\nThe key pattern: no process restart, existing connections continue using the old config, new connections immediately get the updated config.\n\n### Prometheus Implementation\n\n**File Watcher Setup:**\nPrometheus also uses fsnotify for file discovery:\n\n1. `discovery/file/file.go` - The `watchFiles()` method sets watches on configured file paths and directories. The `Run()` method creates `fsnotify.NewWatcher()`, calls `watchFiles()`, then enters select loop handling watcher.Events, ticker.C (periodic refresh), and watcher.Errors. Non-chmod events trigger `refresh()` to re-read target files.\n\n**Config Diff Detection:**\nPrometheus uses SHA256-based checksum for detecting configuration changes:\n\n1. `config/reload.go` - The `GenerateChecksum()` function:\n   - Reads main YAML configuration file\n   - Parses for external file references (rule_files, scrape_config_files)\n   - Generates SHA256 hash of main config content\n   - For each referenced file matching glob patterns, appends to hash: file prefix, file path, and file content\n   - Returns hex-encoded checksum\n   - Handles atomic file writes correctly via glob matching\n\n2. `cmd/prometheus/main.go` - The reload loop:\n   - After successful reload, calls `config.GenerateChecksum()` to get new checksum\n   - On auto-reload polling interval, compares current checksum with stored checksum\n   - Only triggers `reloadConfig()` if checksum differs\n   - This avoids redundant parsing/validation when config unchanged\n\n**Atomic Config Swap:**\nPrometheus distributes config changes to multiple subsystems via `ApplyConfig()` methods:\n\n1. `cmd/prometheus/main.go` - The `reloadConfig()` function:\n   - Loads config via `config.LoadFile()`\n   - Iterates through reloader functions (scrape manager, remote storage, alerting, rules, etc.)\n   - Each reloader's `ApplyConfig(conf)` method handles its portion of configuration\n   - If any reloader fails, entire reload fails and old config remains active\n   - Sets success metrics regardless, allowing monitoring of reload status\n\n2. `scrape/manager.go` - ApplyConfig pattern:\n   - Uses `reflect.DeepEqual(sp.config, cfg)` to detect scrape config changes per job\n   - Uses buffered channel `canReload` to limit concurrent pool reloads\n   - Spawns goroutine per pool to call `sp.reload(cfg)`\n   - Deletes removed pools, updates changed pools in parallel\n   - Returns error if any pool reload fails\n\n3. `scrape/scrape.go` - The `reload()` method:\n   - Updates pool's config reference\n   - Creates new HTTP client from updated config\n   - Calls `restartLoops()` with reuse flag\n   - In `restartLoops()`: for each existing scrape loop, either reuses scrape cache or creates new one\n   - Spawns new scrape loop with updated config but preserves target state and active connections\n   - Closes old HTTP client after new loops started\n   - This ensures no dropped metrics during scrape config changes\n\n4. `tsdb/db.go` - ApplyConfig applies storage config changes:\n   - Updates retention duration atomically via `atomic.Store()`\n   - Updates exemplar and out-of-order time window settings\n   - Calls `head.ApplyConfig()` for in-memory metrics changes\n\n5. `notifier/manager.go` - ApplyConfig for alertmanager discovery:\n   - Applies new alerting configuration\n   - Uses hash matching to preserve existing send loops when possible\n   - Only stops/creates alertmanager connections for changed configs\n\nKey Prometheus pattern: Config hash drives reload decisions → Single `reloadConfig()` function parses once → Multiple `ApplyConfig()` methods atomically update each subsystem → No process restart, existing scrape loops and queries continue uninterrupted.\n\n### Common Patterns\n\nBoth Kubernetes and Prometheus implement:\n1. **File Watchers**: fsnotify for event-driven reloads\n2. **Diff Detection**: Content hashing (SHA256/bytes.Equal) for fast change detection  \n3. **Two-Stage Validation**: Quick hash check, then detailed validation to prevent TOCTOU race conditions\n4. **Work Queues**: Backoff/retry semantics for failed reloads\n5. **Atomic Swaps**: Go's atomic.Value or single-threaded guarantees to swap config without locks\n6. **No Process Restart**: New connections/requests get new config, existing ones continue with old config until completion\n7. **Error Handling**: Failed reloads keep old config active, record metrics, and retry asynchronously"
